    <p id="Par25">The results are shown in Table <xref rid="Tab2" ref-type="table">2</xref>. The data shows a clear time/memory tradeoff for DNA sequences, gsufsort being faster while using approximately 1.25 more memory, gsufsort-light using slightly less memory then mkESA but taking more time. On proteins, gsufsort-light is only marginally slower than gsufsort but faster than mkESA. The authors of mkESA reported a 32% gain on a large protein dataset using 16 threads [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR17">17</xref>], but larger <inline-formula id="IEq87"><alternatives><tex-math id="M153">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
